        <head type="title">&#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D;</head>
        <div type="section" n="title">
            <p>&#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D;</p>
            <p>Ruskin wrote the title as &#x0201C;THE SUN&#x0201D; in both <xref type="mss" doc="mss" target="3">MS III</xref> and MS XI. See <xref
                    type="note" doc="note" target="titlecitation">System of Title Citation for Works</xref>.</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="genre">
            <p><xref type="note" doc="note" target="newyearspoems">New Year&#x02019;s Poem</xref>.</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="facsimiles">
            <p>[none]</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="major ms">
            <p><xref type="mss" doc="mss" target="3">MS III</xref>, MS XI.</p>
            <p>In <xref type="mss" doc="mss" target="3">MS III</xref>, a <xref type="note" doc="note" target="redbook">Red Book</xref> devoted
                initially to <xref type="works" doc="works" target="20">&#x0201C;Harry and Lucy,&#x0201D; Vol. 2</xref>, &#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D; is
                the third poem in the <xref type="note" doc="note" target="msiiipoetryanthology2">MS III Second Poetry Anthology</xref>.</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="date">
            <p>1 January 1828.</p>
            <p>Dated by Ruskin in a presentation copy, MS XI. In this copy, the poem is followed by <xref type="works" doc="works" target="23"
                    >&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x0201D;)</xref>, and the poems follow the same
                order in <xref type="mss" doc="mss" target="3">MS III</xref>, with the date placed between them by Ruskin.</p>
            <p>See <xref type="note" doc="note" target="datecitation">System of Date Citation</xref>.</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="comppub">
            <p>Published with omissions in <xref type="biblio" doc="biblio" target="poems8d1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (8<hi rend="superscript"
                        >o</hi>, 1891)</xref>, 1:5&#x02013;6, and <xref type="biblio" doc="biblio" target="poems4d1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi>
                        (4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</xref>, 1:5&#x02013;6; and in full in <xref type="biblio" doc="biblio"
                    target="jrworksle">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi></xref>, 2:260&#x02013;61.</p>
        </div>
        <div type="section" n="discussion">
            <p>In <xref type="mss" doc="mss" target="3">MS III</xref>, &#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D; shares an interest in constellations with <xref
                    type="works" doc="works" target="20">&#x0201C;Harry and Lucy,&#x0201D; Vol. 2</xref>, and <xref type="works" doc="works"
                    target="21">&#x0201C;The Constellations: Northern, Some of the Zodiac, and Some of the Southern.&#x0201D;</xref> See also <xref
                    type="works" doc="works" target="2">&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x0201D; (&#x0201C;Glen of Glenfarg thy beauteous
                    rill&#x0201D;)</xref>.</p>
        </div>
